column72: feedback. Here, you can give open feedback regarding concerns, improvement proposals and other thoughts.
The vehicle had a couple close calls with pedestrians who were crossing the street. The car did not hit them, but it was too close for comfort.
I saw some errors I do believe in this one, maybe ran a red light and definitely had some pedestrian crossings where the car went to fast and didn't stop for an elderly couple
It would be interesting to have some kind of information regarding the path of the vehicle, what it would do next.

the vehicle came close to a group of people crossing the street about 1/2 -3/4 through video. i couldn`t tell if the vehicle slowed down or not but it didn`t seem to and that is why i recommend speed, turn signal, and brake indicator visuals to make better judgements about the videos.

Everything was fine but, if I were driving, I would have slowed down or stopped for some of the times when pedestrians might be about to step out into the street. As long as all pedestrians stick to crossing the road at traffic lights, I think all would be fine, but if someone tried it where there isn't a light or a stop sign, it would be really dangerous. A human might be looking at the people's facial expressions too, to see what their intentions are and if the pedestrians are paying attention or distracted. The one dangerous part was when a couple were crossing into this car's lane and the car calmly went around them, which was ok, but I would have stopped until they were safely across the road.
I noticed a couple of times the pedestrian icon did not change to dark blue when they were crossing the street.

The vehicle made a bad decision when some pedestrians were crossing the road. Instead of stopping for them it went and could've caused a bad accident. There were some elderly people walking across the street and the man had to stop the women from crossing because he noticed the car was still going.

I realize sometimes when I watch this video I get caught up in the scenary as much as the pedestrians and other vehicles. I feel concentrated but I can imagine after a bit I may get less focused and begin to day dream. Very interesting as always. Its like seeing the world in a another way.
Natural disasters that involve potholes or fallen trees, do you think that automated vehicles will be able to detect them and choose an alternative path for its destination?

At some point in the video (closer to the end), the car did not stop immediately for two people who were crossing a crosswalk. I worried about what the car would do. However, because streetlights are shown on the *side* of the street in this city's location (rather than our streetlights, which hang over the top of the road, directly in front of cars), I was not sure if the car continued driving because there was a green/go light, OR if the light was yellow, and that's why the car was still going. Either way,  I just wanted to mention it to explain why I chose some of my answers about how the car reacted.
I noticed when turning a corner, pedestrians within the turn (on the sidewalk) weren't always highlighted/ noticed.
The car did not stop for certain pedestrians and maintained speed even when they were trying to cross and were already in the road.

I felt the visuals were better this time. I still find the pedestrians the most distracting as I don't like how the status between their states can at times flash back and forth as the car tries to anticipate their movement. I did feel the vehicle's acceleration was slower as it felt like the vehicles around me were moving much faster this time. I also felt there were a few instances where the vehicle started to decelerate too soon and then had to slowly creep up to where it should have stopped. That being said, I am starting to feel more trusting of the vehicle's predictions and behaviours.
